[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Hey everyone, this is a quick high-level look at my video builder for Comfy UI, which is currently in beta testing. This started as a continuation of my earlier node-based music video workflow, but now I\'ve built a UI around it that runs the workflows in the background and adds a'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'lot more tools on top. Even though some parts are still named around music videos, it\'s not only for music. You can use it for music videos, short films, non-vocal videos, visualizers, story scenes, or really any project where you'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'want to build a video scene by scene. This is the main builder. On the left are your scenes, in the middle is your preview. On the right are the settings for the selected scene, and along the bottom is the timeline. Each scene can'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'have timing, notes, prompts, images, video settings, audio, and rendered clips. The wizard is the easiest place to start. It walks you through the general workflow, settings, audio if you\'re using it, lyrics or scene text if'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'needed, generation mode, references, story direction, and then prompting and rendering. You don\'t have to use every step for every project. If you\'re making a non-vocal video or short film, you can treat the lyric areas more like scene'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'structure or story timing. Lyric mapping is where the builder connects the song to the timeline. You can start a few different ways. Transcribe using existing scenes, create scenes from lyrics, or import an SRT file if you'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'already have one. This gives the builder lyric and timing data to work from. After that, you can review and correct the lyrics, map singers, mark instrumental sections, flag B-roll or no lip-sync scenes, and save that mapping'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'back into the project. For music videos, this helps the builder know who should be performing and when. For non-vocal or short-form projects, the same timing ideas can still help organize scene timing, audio structure,'

[01:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'and where different visual beats happen. Reference builder is for consistency. If your project has recurring characters, outfits, props, locations, products, or style references, this is where you organize them. You can add subject'

[01:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'references, create locations, and map them to scenes. That helps the generated images and clips feel like they belong to the same project. The storyboard builder is where you shape the creative direction. This is where you can plan'

[02:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'scene beats, shot style, camera motion, composition, and performance energy. For a song, that might follow lyrics. For a short film, it might follow a script or story outline. For a visualizer, it might follow mood, pacing, and recurring'

[02:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'visual motives. Video builder supports multiple text to image options for when you want to use image to video. This includes Z image, flux client, nano banana, Ernie, and Crea 2 for now, but more will come'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'later. Which one you use depends on your setup and the type of look you want. Some are simpler prompt image workflows, and others can make stronger use of references. Usually, each scene gets an image first, and that image becomes the'

[02:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'visual foundation for the video clip. After the planning and image stages, the builder moves into video prompting and rendering. Video builder supports several video paths: image to video, reference to video using the MSR Laura,'

[02:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'ingredients to video using the ingredients Laura, or plain text video. So, you\'re not locked into only animating a single image. Depending on the workflow, the video can be guided by a starting image, reference material,'

[03:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'ingredient sheet, or just a text prompt. LLMs can help write both image prompts and video prompts using your scene notes, storyboard data, references, timing, and project context. You can use local Gemma, LM Studio, or API-based LLM'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'options. This is where the scene intent, motion direction, camera movement, references, and selected video mode all come together to create the final clip. When the scenes are ready, you can use'

[03:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'batch tools or build full video. The builder can resume missing work, rebuild only certain scenes, render clips, and stitch everything into a final video. This was just the quick overview, and I covered deeper workflows separately,'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'which are on my Discord server. If you want help, examples, or want to follow development, join my Discord. The link is in the description. Thanks for watching. I hope this gave you a good high-level idea of what the video builder can do. I hope to see you on my'

[03:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Discord server.'
